76561198010900149,Recommended,259620,12121850,"Posted: 16 September, 2014",all,daniacea,"If you want a flashy game with the best graphics, one with a linear storyline which guides you by the hand the entire way, look elsewhere. If you enjoy open ended games with tons of replayability you have found a great game.First off I just want to preface this review with saying that I am fascinated with procedural generation in games. The univerese is a unpredictable place with random chance occurrences happening everywhere. It is unpredictability which makes life so diverse and interesing.In this game all chatacters, weapons and the world itself are randomly or procedurally generated. This creates a unique experience everytime you play. It also creates hilarious moments where unexpected things happen.Procedural or random generation is a two sided sword. Because of the random generation, the game experience is not always balanced. Sometimes you will get your *ss handed to you by powerful enemies, sometimes you will find a item which gives you an enormous advantage. The random god giveth and the random god taketh away.I think a good way to judge a game is similar to judging good music. Does it make you experience emotion? In 3079 you will experience every emotion in the spectrum. Happiness when you take out a huge enemy capital ship or find a very good unique weapon. Anger when you see a demon hacking up your fellow humoids, Fear when a demon is pulling you in and you don't have a demon smiter sword and you are over your weight limit on your grappling hook, Exiliration as you fly from mountaintop to mountaintop with a combination of grappling hook and antigravity pack. Pride when you build a inpenetrable underground fortress or capture an enemy building and see your fellow humoids come to inhabit it.My suggestion is to not rush through the game and see how fast you can beat it but to take the time to learn the different styles of gameplay and explore the emmense world created for you.This game is very underated. Most of the bad reviews are from people don't have the patience to learn how to play. You have to be selective in choosing your gear in this game by paying attention to the stats as they vary dramatically. If you just run out into the world with out a strategy you will be slaughtered just like the people who give up after 20 minutes of playing on many of the let's play videos on youtube."
,Not Recommended,259620,11451600,"Posted: 28 July, 2014",all,White Rhino PSO,"Updated ReviewThe first time I played this game, it seemed interesting and quirky. I got some gear and a quest to bring an item to another NPC. To do so I had to shoot the NPC just so he'd come low enough for me to give him the item, as he was a flying guard. I should have known that this would be one of the less aggrivating parts of this game.I started a new game and played for about half an hour. During this time I died five times. I never completed a single quest, and so I made no progress whatsoever. I would explore the different buildings, breaking wooden crates to sell the material right back to the vendors in the same buildings. I would finally have enough to buy an item or two, or sometimes found items while exploring, but none of them seemed to make a difference.The quests I tried to complete are as follows.""Destroy the capital ship."" The small pistol I had bought seemed to have no effect until I got close enough for the ship to open fire on me and reduce me to a fine red paste.""Protect this Humoid for X seconds."" I made it over to the target fine, and things seemed to be all right. Until a hostile flying ship flew over and hammered him into the ground before I could even pull my weapon out. And then it killed me.""Kill X Neanders in X seconds."" This wouldn't be so bad if I wasn't standing in the middle of the Humoid city, and there's no sprint mechanic. With a little abuse of the grapling hook, I was able to quickly hop the nearest wall and went to fight a Neander. This one, the only one in the area, happened to be considered a 'giant' and so was doing ridiculous damage to me. I had previously lost my pistol to a death, so all I had on me was my melee sword.The only time I maybe killed an enemy? When I was on one of the floating buildings, apparently owned by Neanders, and used stealth to hit a guy. The knockback tossing him off the edge of the platform; I have no idea if he actually died or not, because a shopkeeper in the same building quickly killed me again.I'm sure the game might be worth $6.99 to some people, but it's just too tough for me, and I played on the 'normal' difficulty. After the time spent to make zero progress today, though, I don't really see myself playing it again. All in all this game seems like an interesting idea, but it feels like the ideas they put forth - RPG elements, material harvesting and crafting, science fiction storyline - are all handled much better in other games."
